# =============================================================================
# What NOT to send to the Docker build context.
# Reduces upload time to the daemon AND prevents leaking local state
# (secrets, virtualenvs, caches) into any of the image layers.
# =============================================================================

# --- Python ---
# Docker's .dockerignore matches patterns at ROOT unless prefixed with **/,
# so we use **/ for anything that can appear at any depth (like __pycache__
# or node_modules inside src/web/frontend/).
**/__pycache__
**/*.py[cod]
**/*.egg-info
.venv
.uv-cache
.pytest_cache
.ruff_cache
.mypy_cache

# --- Node / build tooling ---
# Excluded EVERYWHERE — Stage 1 runs `npm ci` fresh, doesn't need the local
# node_modules. Same for build outputs. The **/ prefix is critical here:
# without it node_modules only matches at the repo root, not inside
# src/web/frontend/ where it actually lives.
**/node_modules
**/dist
**/*.tsbuildinfo

# --- Frontend build output ---
# Regenerated inside the image by Stage 1 → do not ship the local build.
src/web/static

# --- Secrets & config ---
# .env has real API keys. env.example (no dot) is fine but not needed at
# build time either.
.env
.env.*
!env.example

# --- Version control / metadata ---
.git
.gitignore
.gitattributes
.github

# --- Local tooling / editor state ---
.atl
.claude
.vscode
.idea
*.swp
.DS_Store

# --- Model / dataset caches (if any leaked into the project dir) ---
.cache
models

# --- Docs / brief — not needed at runtime ---
README.md
CLAUDE.md

# --- Local dev orchestration — not deployed with the app ---
docker-compose.yml
scripts

# --- Docker itself — the daemon reads these separately ---
Dockerfile
.dockerignore

# --- Logs ---
*.log
